"CORE_NARRATIVE: Current light field depth estimation is fundamentally bottlenecked by the Lambertian assumption, causing severe failures in real-world scenes dominated by non-Lambertian materials. By introducing an MRI-like k-space angular frequency analysis, we map angular spectra to physical reflection types, establishing a unified optical foundation via a dual-mask physical model. This paradigm shift enables component-aware adaptive depth recovery, effectively breaking the theoretical limits of handling complex diffuse, specular, and scattering reflections.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open with a stark visual or statistical contrast showing the catastrophic depth recovery errors in complex urban environments (e.g., glass, metals) to immediately expose the \"Lambertian assumption bottleneck.\" Frame the failure not as a mere algorithmic flaw, but as a fundamental lack of a unified physical and mathematical model to handle mixed non-Lambertian reflections.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Conclude the related work by arguing that existing techniques merely bypass non-Lambertian regions through heuristic masking or robust cost aggregation, rather than physically modeling the underlying light-matter interactions. This naturally necessitates our transition to the proposed method: building a unified optical foundation from the ground up using MRI-like k-space angular frequency analysis to physically decouple and model mixed reflections.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the dual-mask physical model and 2D-DFT spectral analysis as the exact mathematical mechanisms required to unify Lambertian and non-Lambertian representations based on their distinct spectral energy distributions. Explain that the subsequent component-aware adaptive depth estimation and three-layer progressive wavevector parsing are direct, necessary algorithmic consequences of applying this unified physical prior to resolve depth ambiguities.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Design experiments that explicitly isolate and evaluate performance across pure diffuse, specular, and scattering regions to prove the dual-mask model's physical decoupling capability. Use ablation studies on the 2D-DFT spectral features and confidence-weighted fusion to demonstrate that depth accuracy improvements stem directly from breaking the Lambertian assumption rather than mere network capacity increases.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Reiterate that mapping angular frequency spectra to physical reflection types successfully breaks the Lambertian assumption bottleneck, providing a robust unified optical foundation for non-Lambertian depth recovery. Highlight that this physical modeling paradigm shifts light field vision from idealized geometric assumptions toward true physical optics, paving the way for reliable 3D perception in complex real-world environments."